NT6 – the non‑terminal that must generate the final part of every sentence (because S → NT7 NT6) – can end in only three possible ways:

1. NT6 → 't5' | 't4' | 't9' | 't7' | 't0' | 't2'   (a single terminal)
   → last symbol ∈ {t5, t4, t9, t7, t0, t2}

2. NT6 → NT8 NT9                              (exactly two terminals)
   → last symbol produced by NT9 ∈ {t4, t7, t1, t2, t0, t5}

3. NT6 → NT3 NT5                              (≥2 terminals)
   → last symbol produced by NT5 ∈ {t3, t8, t9, t7, t5, t4}

In every case the last symbol that NT6 can yield is drawn from
{t0, t1, t2, t3, t4, t5, t7, t8, t9} – never t6.

The given string ends with t6, so no derivation can produce it with NT6 at the end, and consequently S cannot derive the string.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

 S → NT7 NT6  

So the given 39‑token string must be splittable into a prefix derived from NT7 and a suffix derived from NT6, with each of those non‑terminals able to generate arbitrary‑length strings of the terminal symbols t0 … t9.

Why this is possible:

1. NT7 rules  
   • NT7 → NT2 NT7 (left‑recursive)  
   • NT7 → NT6 NT3  
   • NT7 → ‘t8’ | ‘t9’ | ‘t1’ | ‘t0’ | ‘t5’ | ‘t4’  

   NT2 can produce any single terminal (directly or through NT8 NT1), so the recursion NT7 → NT2 NT7 lets NT7 add an arbitrary terminal at the left as many times as needed before finally stopping with one of its own six terminal rules or with NT6 NT3 (each of which also covers all terminals). Hence NT7 can generate every finite sequence of terminals of any length ≥ 1.

2. NT6 rules  
   • NT6 → NT8 NT9  
   • NT6 → NT3 NT5  
   • NT6 → ‘t5’ | ‘t4’ | ‘t9’ | ‘t7’ | ‘t0’ | ‘t2’  

   NT8, NT9, NT3 and NT5 together cover all ten terminals, and NT3 is right‑recursive (NT3 → NT3 NT4), so NT6 can yield any string of length 1 (via its direct terminal rules) or any longer length (via its two binary rules, with NT3’s recursion giving unbounded length). Therefore NT6 also generates every finite string of terminals.

3. Because NT7 can produce any non‑empty prefix and NT6 can produce any non‑empty suffix, S can generate every non‑empty string of terminals. In particular, the 39‑token string

 t4 t4 t7 t8 t1 t5 t7 t5 t3 t6 t8 t5 t4 t8 t1 t1 t6 t4 t6 t3
 t4 t6 t6 t6 t6 t7 t4 t2 t9 t9 t7 t9 t7 t3 t6 t4 t8 t1 t1

is certainly obtainable: choose any split point (e.g. after the 20th token), have NT7 derive the 20‑token prefix and NT6 derive the 19‑token suffix, using the recursive additions outlined above.

Hence the grammar does generate the given string.

Yes

The start symbol is  
S → NT7 NT6  

Therefore the string must be splittable into a prefix derived from NT7 and a suffix derived from NT6.

1. NT7  
   • Has direct terminal productions for t0, t1, t4, t5, t8, t9.  
   • Has two recursive binary rules  
     NT7 → NT2 NT7  
     NT7 → NT6 NT3  
     NT2 itself can produce a single terminal (t1, t3, t5, t6, or t7).  
     NT6 and NT3 also can produce at least one terminal (see below).  
   Because of the first recursive rule, NT7 can prepend an arbitrary number of single‑terminal strings (coming from NT2) to whatever NT7 already produces. Consequently NT7 can generate an arbitrary, non‑empty sequence of terminals, provided every terminal is one of  
     {t0, t1, t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9}.  

2. NT6  
   • Direct terminal productions for t0, t2, t4, t5, t7, t9 (length 1 strings).  
   • Binary rules  
     NT6 → NT8 NT9   (length 2 strings, each component a single terminal)  
     NT6 → NT3 NT5   (length ≥2 strings, because NT3 can be arbitrarily long).  
   • The non‑terminal NT3 is unbounded in length owing to the rule NT3 → NT3 NT4 with NT4 → terminal. Hence NT6 can generate a string of any positive length whose terminals are drawn from  
     {t0, t1, t2, t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9}.  

Taken together:

• NT7 can yield any non‑empty sequence of allowed terminals.  
• NT6 can yield any non‑empty sequence of allowed terminals.  
• The allowed terminal set for the union of the two non‑terminals covers every symbol that appears in the given 40‑token string:  
  t0, t1, t2, t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9.

Hence we can split the 40‑token string after any position (e.g. the first token goes to NT7 and the remaining 39 tokens to NT6) and obtain a valid derivation:

S ⇒ NT7 NT6  
   ⇒ (t1) (the rest of the string)  
   where t1 is produced by NT7 directly, and the 39‑token suffix is produced by NT6 via its NT3‑recursion path.

Because such a derivation exists, the grammar does generate the provided string.

Yes
